her husband.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Mental Health Advocates Sue Dukakis, Say Budget CutsUnconstitutional</HEAD><DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Mental health advocates have filed suit againstDemocratic presidential front-runner Gov. Michael Dukakis and histop budget officer.   The suit, filed Wednesday with the state Supreme Court by theAlliance for the Mentally Ill contends that spending cuts orderedto balance the state budget were unconstitutional and would delaycommunity placement of state hospital patients.   Dukakis, whose state budget problems have become an issue in hispresidential campaign, has said the past three years have seen``the most significant expansion in the history of the state'' inspending for the mentally ill.   No hearing date was set.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Gore Says He Won't Try to Influence Convention</HEAD><DATELINE>COOKEVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Sen. Albert Gore Jr., who suspended hisbid for the Democratic presidential nomination in April, says hewon't try to sway actions at the Democratic National Conventionnext month.   ``I would hope that the platform would reflect the kind ofapproach I've recommended,'' Gore said Wednesday on a swing throughhis home state.   ``I think there has already been a shift toward the center onthe part of the other candidates (Massachusetts Gov. MichaelDukakis and Jesse Jackson) as a result of our campaign.''   Gore, 40, still holds a block of about 400 delegates to theconvention in Atlanta, which begins July 18.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>20 Oklahoma Delegates Switch Allegiance To Dukakis</HEAD><DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Most of the Oklahoma delegates previouslypledged to Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore say they will endorseMassachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis for the Democratic presidentialnomination.   The wholesale shift of 20 of the 26 delegates previously pledgedto Gore was announced Wednesday at a news conference at the stateCapitol by Stratton Taylor, a state senator who is chairman ofGore's Oklahoma campaign.   Sen. David Boren, D-Okla., also formerly a Gore supporter joinedthe group's switch.   ``He has clearly emerged as the strong front-runner for thenomination and is now entitled to have consensus support from theparty as we move toward the national convention in Atlanta,'' saidBoren.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Grassley, Branstad Join Forces To Run Bush Campaign</HEAD><DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Gov. Terry Branstad and Sen. CharlesGrassley, often at odds with each other, say they will join forcesto run George Bush's Iowa presidential campaign.   Branstad and Grassley formally announced their decision at aStatehouse news conference Wednesday, saying that gives the vicepresident a chance at carrying the state in November though ``weknow it won't be easy.''   ``We can carry Iowa in November,'' Branstad said.   ``There should be no doubt any more'' that the state'sRepublican Party is united after an often-fractious campaign forthe Feb. 8 precinct caucuses, said Grassley.   Grassley was a prominent backer of Kansas Sen. Bob Dole duringthat caucus campaign, while Branstad was neutral.</TEXT></DOC>